The paper deals with a data-driven investigation of message spreading in a real-world dynamical network of human proximity. This involves the use of wearable sensors and the analysis of the topological and temporal properties of the proximity network. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also deals with the simulation of message spreading and the validation of established models of human mobility and proximity, which could fall under cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks). Additionally, the use of wearable sensors and the analysis of data could also fall under cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy).
